text.tspan: Projected changes in streamflow (% difference
from 1961-1990) indicate a decrease in summer
flows and an increase in winter flows for
catchments situated throughout Ireland
(Steele-Dunne et al. 1998)
Coastal Erosion
Rising sea levels combined with increased wave heights and
more intense surges will put all of Ireland's coastal areas at
risk of coastal erosion, northeastern and southwestern coasts
in particular. In the map above, areas currently at risk of erosion
are marked in red.
Coastal Flooding
Increasing sea levels combined with increased wave heights and
storm surge intensity will put Ireland's coastal infrastructure at risk
and this includes Ireland's major cities. In addition, due to increased
levels of winter precipitation, when combined with increased levels
of river flow, innundation of Ireland's major cities is of concern.
Inland Flooding
Increased levels of winter precipitation will result in an
increased risk of inland flooding with new areas, previously
not subject to flooding being put at risk.
Drought
Decreased levels of summer precipitation, particularly in the
south and south east, may result in the increased occurrence
of drought conditions. This will put water supply at risk due
to low flows and increased risk of contamination.
Growing Season
Increasing temperatures will serve to prolong the growing season with spring
occuring earlier. Increasing temperatures may also serve to increase yields.
However, this increase may be offset by decreased levels of water availability
Biodiversity Loss
Projected shifts in climate and sea level rise will impact
upon the geographical range and phenology (timing of
lifecycle events) of species native to Ireland, resulting in
biodiversity and ecosystem loss. In addition, the occurence
of invasive species is expected to increase under projected
climate change.
